tips.dat
msg_ui_tips_page	[VAR 0201(0000)]/[VAR 0201(0001)]
msg_ui_tips_title_00	Survey Tips
msg_ui_tips_option_01	Next
msg_ui_tips_option_02	Exit
tips_title_000	Checking Survey Tips
tips_text_000_01	Survey tips contain all sorts of useful information to help you\ncarry out your survey work in the Hisui region.\n\nTo read them at any time, simply press the [VAR FF00(0006)]Up Button[VAR FF00(0000)] to open\nthe menu, then go to the Help screen.
tips_title_010	Throwing Poké Balls
tips_text_010_01	Pokémon can be caught by throwing Poké Balls at them.\n\n[VAR FF00(0006)]Hold down[VAR FF00(0000)] the ZR Button to ready a Poké Ball and take aim.\nYou can keep moving around as you do, so use the Right Stick\nto adjust your angle and aim carefully at your target Pokémon.
tips_text_010_02	[VAR FF00(0006)]Release[VAR FF00(0000)] the ZR Button to throw the Poké Ball. If it hits a\nPokémon, you may be able to catch it.\n\nIf you’ve readied a Poké Ball but do not want to throw it,\npress the B Button to cancel the throw.
tips_title_020	Starting Pokémon Battles
tips_text_020_01	It’s easy to start a battle against a wild Pokémon—simply throw\na Poké Ball that contains one of your own Pokémon at it.\nIf you can see that you currently have an item readied to throw,\nnot a Pokémon, press the [VAR FF00(0006)]X Button[VAR FF00(0000)]. It will allow you to toggle\nbetween your thrown items and your Pokémon team.
tips_title_025	The Secret Back Strike Technique
tips_text_025_01	Hit a wild Pokémon from behind for a higher chance\nof a successful catch or to gain an advantage when\nstarting a battle.\n\nThis secret technique is called a [VAR FF00(0006)]back strike[VAR FF00(0000)].
tips_title_030	Focusing in the Field
tips_text_030_01	[VAR FF00(0006)]Hold down[VAR FF00(0000)] the ZL Button to focus on a wild Pokémon\nand keep it in your sights as long as it’s nearby.\n\nThis technique comes in very useful when aiming Poké Balls\nat a target or when dodging Pokémon’s attacks.
tips_title_040	Take Cues by Focusing
tips_text_040_01	When you use the ZL Button to focus on a Pokémon,\nyou can see how easy it may be to catch.\n\nThe more [VAR FF00(0006)]arrows [VAR FF00(0000)]you see pointing up above a Pokémon,\nthe easier it will be to catch.
tips_text_040_02	An [VAR FF00(0006)]X icon[VAR FF00(0000)] will appear above a Pokémon if it has picked a\nfight with you.\n\nBe warned—Pokémon displaying this icon [VAR FF00(0006)]cannot be caught\nunless you engage them in battle[VAR FF00(0000)]!
tips_title_050	Crouching Down
tips_text_050_01	Press the B Button to crouch and make it harder for wild\nPokémon to notice you. Press the same button again to rise.\n\nIf you creep into the tall grass while crouched low, you’ll be\neven harder for wild Pokémon to detect.
tips_title_055	Dodging Pokémon Attacks
tips_text_055_01	When you press the Y Button to dodge, you’ll become\n[VAR FF00(0006)]invulnerable [VAR FF00(0000)]to Pokémon attacks for a brief moment.\nDodge with just the right timing to pass through incoming\nattacks without taking any damage!
tips_title_060	The Dangers of Taking Damage
tips_text_060_01	If you take too much damage within a short time, you’ll be\n[VAR FF00(0006)]in danger of blacking out[VAR FF00(0000)]. You can tell you’re in danger\nwhen the edges of the screen turn red.\nDamage goes away over time, but you won’t begin to recover\nif you’re still being targeted by a wild Pokémon.
tips_text_060_02	If you take further damage after the edges of the screen have\nturned red, you’ll become overwhelmed and black out.
tips_title_070	Research Tasks
tips_text_070_01	Research tasks are [VAR FF00(0006)]tasks you need to carry out to complete the[VAR FF00(0000)]\n[VAR FF00(0006)]Pokédex[VAR FF00(0000)]. Each Pokémon species has a different number and\nvariety of research tasks. Press the Down Button to open your\nPokédex, then check what kinds of research tasks are available\nfor the Pokémon you’ve registered.
tips_text_070_02	When you’ve focused on a wild Pokémon in the field using\nthe ZL Button, you can also [VAR FF00(0006)]instantly check[VAR FF00(0000)] the research\ntasks for that species by pressing the Down Button to open\nyour Pokédex right to that page. Some Pokémon have some\nunusual research tasks, so be sure to check them out.
tips_title_075	Unown Research Notes
tips_text_075_01	Press the Y Button while viewing the cover of your Pokédex to\njump to your Unown research notes.\n\nBy deciphering the cryptic symbols found in these notes, you\ncan try to find all the Unown hiding throughout the region.\n\nThese Unown possess a mysterious power that repels Poké Balls\ncontaining Pokémon, so you won’t be able to battle them, but\ntrack them down and catch them all if you can!
tips_title_080	Earn Money for Survey Reports
tips_text_080_01	When you submit survey reports, you’ll receive [VAR FF00(0006)]money[VAR FF00(0000)]\nbased on the level and number of Pokémon you’ve caught.\n\nYou’ll receive more money if you’ve fulfilled certain conditions,\nsuch as catching a species for the first time.
tips_title_085	Completing the Pokédex
tips_text_085_01	By carrying out research tasks and submitting survey reports,\nyou’ll raise the [VAR FF00(0006)]research levels[VAR FF00(0000)] of the Pokémon species you\nencounter. If you raise a Pokémon’s entry to [VAR FF00(0006)]level 10[VAR FF00(0000)], that entry\nwill be considered [VAR FF00(0006)]complete [VAR FF00(0000)]and you will have unlocked all of\nthe detailed information to be had about that species.
tips_text_085_02	As you carry out tasks and complete the Pokédex entries for\ndifferent species, you’ll also gain [VAR FF00(0006)]Pokémon research points[VAR FF00(0000)],\nwhich you can view on the cover of your Pokédex.\nOnce you’ve earned a certain number of points, you’ll be able\nto move up through the ranks of the Galaxy Expedition Team.
tips_title_090	The Map and Markers
tips_text_090_01	Use the − Button to view the [VAR FF00(0006)]map[VAR FF00(0000)] on your Arc Phone.\n\nYou can consult the map for guidance to your next destination\nand information on your missions and requests.
tips_text_090_02	You’ll also see [VAR FF00(0006)]guidance markers[VAR FF00(0000)] when you’re out exploring\nor running around the village.\n\nIf you’re not sure where to go next, stop and look around in all\ndirections to try to spot one of these markers, then head for it!
tips_title_100	Instant Travel
tips_text_100_01	Press the X Button while consulting the map on your Arc Phone\nto [VAR FF00(0006)]instantly travel[VAR FF00(0000)] to base camps and other locations.\n\nHowever, be aware that this feature might not be usable in\nsome situations.
tips_title_110	Checking Missions & Requests
tips_text_110_01	Press the Y Button while consulting the map on your Arc Phone,\nand you can check the tasks you have waiting. There are two\ntypes: missions and requests.\n\n[VAR FF00(0006)]Missions[VAR FF00(0000)] must be completed to progress in your adventure,\nwhile [VAR FF00(0006)]requests[VAR FF00(0000)] are optional and given by people you meet.
tips_title_115	Accepting Requests
tips_text_115_01	People who have something to ask you will have a [VAR FF00(0006)]request icon[VAR FF00(0000)]\ndisplayed above them.\n\nIf you fulfill their request, you may receive a nice reward.
tips_title_120	Riding on Pokémon
tips_text_120_01	Press the + Button to summon a Pokémon to ride on.\n\nBe sure to stay alert for wild Pokémon attacks and avoid\nfalls from high places while you’re riding about!
tips_title_130	Digging for Treasure with Ursaluna
tips_text_130_01	Ursaluna will rush toward any treasure he senses in front of him.\nPress the Y Button to [VAR FF00(0006)]dig for treasure[VAR FF00(0000)] when Ursaluna finds a spot\nthat makes him react particularly strongly. You might find\nsomething very nice!
tips_title_132	Traversing Water with Basculegion
tips_text_132_01	Press the + Button or A Button when you’re in the water\nto summon Basculegion and cross the water on his back.
tips_text_132_02	While riding Basculegion, you’ll still be able to throw items.\n\nWhat’s more, when Basculegion jumps into the air, you’ll have\nmore time to adjust your aim before you throw.
tips_title_134	Climbing with Sneasler
tips_text_134_01	You can climb up and down cliffs, ledges, and other sheer\nsurfaces with Sneasler’s aid.\n\nTo summon Sneasler, press the A Button when you’re near a\nclimbable surface or use the + Button in any other location.
tips_title_136	Soaring the Skies with Braviary
tips_text_136_01	With Braviary, you can fly high up into the sky and explore the\ndifferent areas of Hisui from the air. You can summon Braviary\nusing the + Button wherever you may be, and you can also press\nthe A Button if you’re falling from some height to summon him\nin a flash.
tips_title_140	Crafting Items
tips_text_140_01	You can use the [VAR FF00(0006)]workbenches [VAR FF00(0000)]in Jubilife Village and the base\ncamps to craft Poké Balls and other items.\n\nCrafting items requires a recipe and the necessary materials.
tips_text_140_02	Once you’ve acquired a [VAR FF00(0006)]Crafting Kit[VAR FF00(0000)], you can craft items\nwherever and whenever you like. However, unlike at a\nworkbench, you’ll only be able to use the materials in your\nsatchel, and you won’t be able to craft more items than\nyour satchel can hold.
tips_title_145	The Crafting Kit
tips_text_145_01	You can select the [VAR FF00(0006)]Crafting Kit [VAR FF00(0000)]from the Key Items pocket in\nyour satchel to craft items wherever and whenever you like.\nHowever, unlike at a workbench, you’ll only be able to use the\nmaterials in your satchel, and you won’t be able to craft more\nitems than your satchel can hold.
tips_title_150	Evolving Pokémon
tips_text_150_01	Some Pokémon can undergo Evolution, which changes their\nappearance and stats. If one of your Pokémon has met the\nrequirements to evolve, you’ll be able to select the [VAR FF00(0006)]Evolve\n[VAR FF00(0000)]option when viewing the Pokémon in your satchel.
tips_title_160	Alpha Pokémon
tips_text_160_01	Pokémon whose eyes glow red are called [VAR FF00(0006)]alpha Pokémon[VAR FF00(0000)].\n\nAlpha Pokémon are larger than others and may know\nmoves that are rare for their species. They appear to\nbe very difficult to catch.
tips_title_170	Space-Time Distortions
tips_text_170_01	[VAR FF00(0006)]Space-time distortions[VAR FF00(0000)] are dangerous places where\npowerful Pokémon appear.\n\nHowever, if you’re brave enough to enter them, you might\nbe able to find rare Pokémon and items inside.
tips_title_180	Type Matchups
tips_text_180_01	Both Pokémon and moves have [VAR FF00(0006)]types[VAR FF00(0000)]. The type matchup\nbetween a move and its target Pokémon determines how much\ndamage is taken. Moves can be super effective, effective, not\nvery effective, or completely ineffective.
tips_text_180_02	Here are some examples of type matchups:\n\nFire-type moves are strong against Grass-type Pokémon.\nGrass-type moves are strong against Water-type Pokémon.\nWater-type moves are strong against Fire-type Pokémon.
tips_title_190	Pokémon Moves
tips_text_190_01	Pokémon sometimes learn new moves when they level up.\n\nIf you want to change the moves your Pokémon can use in\nbattle, open your satchel, choose the Pokémon you want,\nand select the [VAR FF00(0006)]Change moves[VAR FF00(0000)] option.
tips_title_200	Action Speed in Battle
tips_text_200_01	Press the Y Button during battle to check the [VAR FF00(0006)]action order [VAR FF00(0000)]of\nall the Pokémon currently battling. This shows the order in\nwhich Pokémon will take their upcoming turns, based on their\n[VAR FF00(0006)]action speed[VAR FF00(0000)].\n\nThe action speed of a Pokémon is based on its Speed stat,\nbut it can also be affected by certain moves and items.\nA Pokémon with a high action speed may be able to act multiple\ntimes in a row.
tips_title_210	Agile Style and Strong Style Moves
tips_text_210_01	Once your Pokémon has mastered a move, you can have it use\nthe move in either the [VAR FF00(0006)]agile style[VAR FF00(0000)] or [VAR FF00(0006)]strong style[VAR FF00(0000)] by pressing the\nL or R Button, or the Left or Right Button, when selecting the\nmove in battle.\n\nSometimes your Pokémon will naturally master a move and\nunlock these extra styles simply by leveling up.
tips_text_210_02	Agile Style\n・Reduces the power of the move\n・Raises the user’s action speed\n・Uses more PP than usual\n\nStrong Style\n・Boosts the power of the move\n・Lowers the user’s action speed\n・Uses more PP than usual
tips_title_215	Saving Your Progress
tips_text_215_01	To save your progress, press the Up Button to open the\nmenu, then scroll with the ZL or ZR Button until you reach\nthe Save screen.\n\nThere is also an [VAR FF00(0006)]autosave[VAR FF00(0000)] function you can use to have your\nprogress saved automatically.\n\nYou can enable or disable autosave by scrolling to the Help\nscreen in the menu, then selecting Settings.
tips_title_220	The Lost & Found
tips_text_220_01	If you black out in the field, you may lose some of your items.\nHowever, players from all over the world can find your lost\nitems and send them to you via the internet. This system is\ncalled the Lost & Found.
tips_text_220_02	If you find a satchel that someone else has lost, be sure to\npick it up. The satchel you retrieved will be returned to its\nowner, and you can receive [VAR FF00(0006)]Merit Points [VAR FF00(0000)]([VAR FF00(0006)]MP[VAR FF00(0000)]) as a reward.
tips_text_220_03	[VAR FF00(0006)]MP [VAR FF00(0000)]can be exchanged for items at the trading post in Jubilife\nVillage. Pick up lost satchels whenever you find them, and you\nmay be able to get your hands on some very special items!
tips_title_230	Mystery Gifts
tips_text_230_01	You can receive Pokémon, items, and other special gifts via the\ninternet or by using codes or passwords.\n\nBe sure to keep an eye on the latest Pokémon news for\ninformation about any available Mystery Gifts.
tips_title_240	Taking Screenshots
tips_text_240_01	Press the [VAR FF00(0006)]Capture Button [VAR FF00(0000)]to save still images of your game.\nYou can view these screenshots in the Album on the\nHOME Menu of your Nintendo Switch system.

tips_title_260	Battling Pokémon Nobles
tips_text_260_01	To claim victory against a noble Pokémon and quell its\nfrenzy, you’ll have to throw balms at it until its frenzy\ngauge reaches zero.
tips_text_260_02	If you manage to create an opening in the noble’s defenses,\nyou’ll be able to send out your Pokémon to battle against it.\nWin the Pokémon battle, and the noble’s guard will stay down\nfor a brief time. During that window, balms will be more\neffective than usual, so throw as many as you can.
tips_title_270	Focusing on a Noble
tips_text_270_01	The ZL Button can also be used to focus on a noble Pokémon\nwhile you are facing off against it.\n\nObserve your opponent’s movements carefully to dodge its\nattacks and seize opportunities to throw balms.
tips_title_280	The Powerful Attacks of Nobles
tips_text_280_01	When a noble Pokémon starts accumulating energy, that means\nit’s preparing to launch a powerful attack.\n\nHit it with as many balms as you can during this phase in order\nto stop that attack in its tracks.

tips_text_1001_01	When Kleavor charges at you, dodge to the side using the\nY Button to evade his swinging axes. If you’ve positioned\nyourself well, he may crash into a wall or the tree in the center\nof the arena. This will be your chance to throw one of your\nparty Pokémon’s Poké Balls and initiate a [VAR FF00(0006)]Pokémon battle[VAR FF00(0000)]!
tips_title_1002	Battling Lilligant
tips_text_1002_01	Press the Y Button at the right moment to dodge Lilligant’s\nwave attacks as they ripple out toward you. Remember that\nyou’re [VAR FF00(0006)]invulnerable [VAR FF00(0000)]while dodging, so you can pass through\nthe attacks without taking any damage.

tips_title_1004	Battling Electrode
tips_text_1004_01	When it looks like Electrode is about to explode, hurry and\nget as far from it as possible! After the explosion, don’t miss\nthe opportunity to send out your Pokémon to face Electrode\nin battle.

btl_state.dat
BTR_STATE_00_01	[~ 0]
BTR_STATE_00_02	[~ 1]
BTR_STATE_01_01	Harsh Sunlight
BTR_STATE_01_02	The harsh sunlight weather condition.\nIt boosts the power of Fire-type moves and\nlowers the power of Water-type moves.
BTR_STATE_02_01	Rain
BTR_STATE_02_02	The rain weather condition.\nIt boosts the power of Water-type moves and\nlowers the power of Fire-type moves.
BTR_STATE_03_01	Sandstorm
BTR_STATE_03_02	The sandstorm weather condition.\nAt the end of each turn, it damages all Pokémon\nthat are not Rock, Ground, or Steel types.\nIt boosts the Sp. Def of Rock-type Pokémon.
BTR_STATE_04_01	Hail
BTR_STATE_04_02	The hail weather condition.\nAt the end of each turn, it damages all Pokémon\nthat are not Ice types.
BTR_STATE_05_01	Electric Terrain
BTR_STATE_05_02	For five turns, Pokémon on the ground won’t\nfall asleep.\nThe power of Electric-type moves is boosted.
BTR_STATE_06_01	Grassy Terrain
BTR_STATE_06_02	For five turns, Pokémon on the ground will have\na little HP restored at the end of each turn.\nThe power of Grass-type moves is boosted.
BTR_STATE_07_01	Misty Terrain
BTR_STATE_07_02	For five turns, Pokémon on the ground won’t get\nany status conditions.\nDamage from Dragon-type moves is halved.
BTR_STATE_08_01	Trick Room
BTR_STATE_08_02	Slower Pokémon get to move first for five turns.
BTR_STATE_09_01	Magic Room
BTR_STATE_09_02	Pokémon can’t use their held items for five turns.
BTR_STATE_10_01	Wonder Room
BTR_STATE_10_02	Pokémon’s Defense and Sp. Def are swapped for\nfive turns.
BTR_STATE_11_01	Critical Hit Boost
BTR_STATE_11_02	The Pokémon is more likely to land critical hits.
BTR_STATE_12_01	Confusion
BTR_STATE_12_02	The Pokémon may hurt itself in its confusion.\nThe effect lasts for one to four turns.
BTR_STATE_13_01	Infatuation
BTR_STATE_13_02	The Pokémon is less likely to unleash an attack\non Pokémon of the opposite gender.
BTR_STATE_14_01	Nightmare
BTR_STATE_14_02	The Pokémon will lose HP each turn as long as\nit is sleeping.
BTR_STATE_15_01	Drowsy
BTR_STATE_15_02	The Pokémon will become drowsy at the end of\nthe turn if it remains on the battlefield.
BTR_STATE_16_01	Encore
BTR_STATE_16_02	Due to Encore, the Pokémon can use only\n[VAR 0107(0000)] for three turns.
BTR_STATE_17_01	No Ability
BTR_STATE_17_02	The Pokémon’s Ability loses its effect.
BTR_STATE_18_01	Torment
BTR_STATE_18_02	The Pokémon can’t use the same move twice\nin a row.
BTR_STATE_19_01	Tailwind
BTR_STATE_19_02	The Speed stats of a Pokémon and its allies are\ndoubled for four turns.
BTR_STATE_20_01	Lucky Chant
BTR_STATE_20_02	The opponent’s moves won’t result in a\ncritical hit.
BTR_STATE_21_01	Grudge
BTR_STATE_21_02	If the Pokémon faints by an opponent’s move,\nthe PP of that move will be reduced to 0.
BTR_STATE_22_01	Heal Block
BTR_STATE_22_02	For five turns, the Pokémon is unable to recover\nHP through its moves, Ability, or held item.
BTR_STATE_23_01	Identified
BTR_STATE_23_02	The Pokémon will be hit by certain moves\nthat usually wouldn’t affect it.\nIf the Pokémon’s evasiveness has been boosted,\nthe benefits will be ignored when it is attacked.
BTR_STATE_24_01	Move Disabled
BTR_STATE_24_02	For four turns, the Pokémon will be unable to\nuse [VAR 0107(0000)].
BTR_STATE_25_01	Can’t Escape
BTR_STATE_25_02	The Pokémon can’t flee or be switched out.
BTR_STATE_26_01	Lock-On
BTR_STATE_26_02	The next move used by the Pokémon will be sure\nto hit the target that was locked on to.
BTR_STATE_27_01	Embargo
BTR_STATE_27_02	For five turns, the Pokémon cannot use its held\nitem and no items can be used on it.
BTR_STATE_28_01	Charge
BTR_STATE_28_02	The power of an Electric-type move will be\ndoubled if used in the turn after charging.
BTR_STATE_29_01	Gravity
BTR_STATE_29_02	Moves are more likely to hit for five turns.\nGround-type moves will hit Flying-type\nPokémon and Pokémon with the Levitate Ability.\nMoves that require action midair can’t be used.
BTR_STATE_30_01	Mist
BTR_STATE_30_02	The Pokémon’s stats won’t be lowered for\nfive turns.
BTR_STATE_31_01	Safeguard
BTR_STATE_31_02	The Pokémon is protected from status conditions\nfor five turns.
BTR_STATE_32_01	Stealth Rock
BTR_STATE_32_02	Pokémon that switch into battle will\ntake damage.
BTR_STATE_33_01	Stockpile
BTR_STATE_33_02	The Pokémon’s Defense and Sp. Def stats\ngo up while stockpiling.
BTR_STATE_34_01	Taunt
BTR_STATE_34_02	The Pokémon can only use moves that\ndeal damage.
BTR_STATE_35_01	Telekinesis
BTR_STATE_35_02	For three turns, moves used against\nthe Pokémon will hit without fail, except for\none-hit KO moves.\nAlso, Ground-type moves won’t hit\nthe Pokémon.
BTR_STATE_36_01	Magnet Rise
BTR_STATE_36_02	Ground-type moves won’t hit the Pokémon\nfor five turns.
BTR_STATE_37_01	Toxic Spikes
BTR_STATE_37_02	Pokémon that switch into battle will\nbe poisoned.\nFlying-type Pokémon or Pokémon with\nthe Levitate Ability will not be affected.
BTR_STATE_38_01	Mud Sport
BTR_STATE_38_02	The power of Electric-type moves will be\nhalved for five turns.
BTR_STATE_39_01	Wish
BTR_STATE_39_02	The Pokémon in this spot will have its HP restored\non the turn after Wish was used.
BTR_STATE_40_01	Sticky Web
BTR_STATE_40_02	Pokémon that switch into battle will have their\nSpeed lowered.
BTR_STATE_41_01	Ingrain
BTR_STATE_41_02	The Pokémon regains some HP at the end of\neach turn.\nIngrained Pokémon can’t be switched out.
BTR_STATE_42_01	Curse
BTR_STATE_42_02	The Pokémon takes damage at the end\nof each turn.
BTR_STATE_43_01	Trick-or-Treat
BTR_STATE_43_02	The Pokémon gains the Ghost type.
BTR_STATE_44_01	Light Screen
BTR_STATE_44_02	Damage from special moves is halved for\nfive turns.
BTR_STATE_45_01	Reflect
BTR_STATE_45_02	Damage from physical moves is halved for\nfive turns.
BTR_STATE_46_01	Imprison
BTR_STATE_46_02	If a Pokémon affected by Imprison knows any\nmoves also known by the user of Imprison, it is\nprevented from using those moves.
BTR_STATE_47_01	Counting Down
BTR_STATE_47_02	All Pokémon in this battle state will faint after\nthree turns.
BTR_STATE_48_01	Spikes
BTR_STATE_48_02	Pokémon that switch into battle will\ntake damage.\nFlying-type Pokémon or Pokémon with\nthe Levitate Ability will not be affected.
BTR_STATE_49_01	Water Sport
BTR_STATE_49_02	The power of Fire-type moves will be\nhalved for five turns.
BTR_STATE_50_01	Destiny Bond
BTR_STATE_50_02	If the Pokémon is knocked out by an opponent,\nthat opponent will also faint.
BTR_STATE_51_01	Forest’s Curse
BTR_STATE_51_02	The Pokémon gains the Grass type.
BTR_STATE_52_01	Leech Seed
BTR_STATE_52_02	Leech Seed steals some of the Pokémon’s HP\nat the end of each turn and gives it to\nthe opponent.
BTR_STATE_53_01	Lock-On
BTR_STATE_53_02	Any move used against a locked-on target will\nbe sure to hit.
BTR_STATE_54_01	Bound
BTR_STATE_54_02	The Pokémon is bound and takes damage\nevery turn.
BTR_STATE_55_01	Bide
BTR_STATE_55_02	The Pokémon endures attacks for two turns,\nthen strikes back to inflict double the\ndamage it has taken.
BTR_STATE_56_01	Outrage
BTR_STATE_56_02	The Pokémon rampages and attacks for two to\nthree turns. It then becomes confused.
BTR_STATE_57_01	Rampaging
BTR_STATE_57_02	The Pokémon rampages and attacks for two to\nthree turns. It then becomes confused.
BTR_STATE_58_01	Petal Dance
BTR_STATE_58_02	The Pokémon rampages and attacks for two to\nthree turns. It then becomes confused.
BTR_STATE_59_01	Badly Poisoned
BTR_STATE_59_02	The Pokémon is badly poisoned. The damage\nthe Pokémon takes from the poison worsens\nevery turn.
BTR_STATE_60_01	Future Attack
BTR_STATE_60_02	The Pokémon will take damage two turns after\nan attack was foreseen.
BTR_STATE_61_01	Uproar
BTR_STATE_61_02	The Pokémon attacks and causes an uproar for\nthree turns. During this time, no Pokémon can\nfall asleep.
BTR_STATE_62_01	Aqua Ring
BTR_STATE_62_02	The Pokémon is enveloped in a veil made of\nwater. It regains some HP every turn.
BTR_STATE_63_01	Autotomize
BTR_STATE_63_02	The Pokémon’s weight is reduced, and its Speed\nis sharply increased.
BTR_STATE_64_01	Smack Down
BTR_STATE_64_02	The Pokémon has been knocked out of the sky\nand has fallen to the ground.
BTR_STATE_65_01	Fairy Lock
BTR_STATE_65_02	No Pokémon can flee the turn after Fairy Lock\nis used.
BTR_STATE_66_01	Rainbow
BTR_STATE_66_02	The additional effects of moves are more likely\nto occur.
BTR_STATE_67_01	Swamp
BTR_STATE_67_02	Speed is reduced by 75% in swampy conditions.
BTR_STATE_68_01	Sea of Fire
BTR_STATE_68_02	Pokémon that are not Fire types will\ntake damage every turn.
BTR_STATE_69_01	Extremely Harsh Sunlight
BTR_STATE_69_02	The extremely harsh sunlight weather condition.\nIt boosts the power of Fire-type moves and\nprotects Pokémon from Water-type moves.
BTR_STATE_70_01	Heavy Rain
BTR_STATE_70_02	The heavy rain weather condition.\nIt boosts the power of Water-type moves and\nprotects Pokémon from Fire-type moves.
BTR_STATE_71_01	Strong Winds
BTR_STATE_71_02	The strong winds weather condition.\nThe power of moves that are super effective\nagainst Flying-type Pokémon is decreased.
BTR_STATE_72_01	Psychic Terrain
BTR_STATE_72_02	For five turns, Pokémon on the ground won’t be\nhit by priority moves.\nThe power of Psychic-type moves is boosted.
BTR_STATE_73_01	Throat Chop
BTR_STATE_73_02	The Pokémon can’t use any sound-based moves\nfor two turns.
BTR_STATE_74_01	Aurora Veil
BTR_STATE_74_02	For five turns, the power of special and physical\nmoves will be halved.
BTR_STATE_75_01	Laser Focus
BTR_STATE_75_02	The next move used will always result in\na critical hit.
BTR_STATE_76_01	Tar Shot
BTR_STATE_76_02	The Pokémon has been made weaker to\nFire-type moves.
BTR_STATE_77_01	Octolock
BTR_STATE_77_02	The Pokémon’s Defense and Sp. Def are both\nlowered with each passing turn.
BTR_STATE_78_01	G-Max Wildfire
BTR_STATE_78_02	Pokémon that are not Fire types will take\ndamage every turn for four turns.
BTR_STATE_79_01	G-Max Volcalith
BTR_STATE_79_02	Pokémon that are not Rock types will take\ndamage every turn for four turns.
BTR_STATE_80_01	G-Max Steelsurge
BTR_STATE_80_02	Pokémon that switch into battle will\ntake damage.
BTR_STATE_81_01	G-Max Vine Lash
BTR_STATE_81_02	Pokémon that are not Grass types will take\ndamage every turn for four turns.
BTR_STATE_82_01	G-Max Cannonade
BTR_STATE_82_02	Pokémon that are not Water types will take\ndamage every turn for four turns.
BTR_STATE_83_01	Fixated
BTR_STATE_83_02	The Pokémon is fixated on the last move it\nused. This move will deal increased damage\nwhile the fixation lasts, but any damage dealt to\nthe fixated Pokémon is also increased.
BTR_STATE_84_01	Splinters
BTR_STATE_84_02	At the end of each turn, the Pokémon is hurt\nby the jagged splinters digging into it.
BTR_STATE_85_01	Obscured
BTR_STATE_85_02	The Pokémon is concealed in mud or the like,\nraising the chance that the Pokémon will evade\nopponents’ moves.
BTR_STATE_86_01	Primed
BTR_STATE_86_02	The Pokémon has adopted a hard-hitting stance,\nincreasing the damage it deals with its moves.
BTR_STATE_87_01	Stance Swap
BTR_STATE_87_02	The Pokémon has swapped its offensive stats\nwith its defensive stats.
BTR_STATE_88_01	Slow Start
BTR_STATE_88_02	The Pokémon’s Attack and Speed stats are\nhalved until it gets going.
BTR_STATE_89_01	Frenzied Might
BTR_STATE_89_02	The Pokémon takes reduced damage from status\nconditions and move effects such as poisoning\nand splinters.
BTR_STATE_90_01	Poisoned
BTR_STATE_90_02	At the end of each turn, the Pokémon is hurt\nby poison.
BTR_STATE_91_01	Paralyzed
BTR_STATE_91_02	The Pokémon is paralyzed and may fail to act.\nIts Speed stat is also lowered.
BTR_STATE_92_01	Drowsy
BTR_STATE_92_02	The Pokémon is drowsy and may fail to act.\nAny damage it takes is also increased.
BTR_STATE_93_01	Burned
BTR_STATE_93_02	At the end of each turn, the Pokémon is hurt\nby its burn. Any damage it deals with physical\nmoves will also be reduced.
BTR_STATE_94_01	Frostbite
BTR_STATE_94_02	At the end of each turn, the Pokémon is hurt\nby its frostbite. Any damage it deals with special\nmoves will also be reduced.
BTR_STATE_95_01	Wild Might
BTR_STATE_95_02	All the Pokémon’s stats are boosted. The\nPokémon also takes reduced damage from status\nconditions and move effects such as poisoning\nand splinters.
BTR_STATE_96_01	Terrific Might
BTR_STATE_96_02	The Pokémon takes reduced damage from status\nconditions and move effects such as poisoning\nand splinters.
BTR_STATE_97_01	Terrible Might
BTR_STATE_97_02	All the Pokémon’s stats are boosted. The\nPokémon also takes reduced damage from status\nconditions and move effects such as poisoning\nand splinters.
BTR_STATE_98_01	Power Boost
BTR_STATE_98_02	The Pokémon’s offensive stats are raised,\nboosting its Attack and Sp. Atk stats.
BTR_STATE_99_01	Power Drop
BTR_STATE_99_02	The Pokémon’s offensive stats are lowered,\nreducing its Attack and Sp. Atk stats.
BTR_STATE_100_01	Guard Boost
BTR_STATE_100_02	The Pokémon’s defensive stats are raised,\nboosting its Defense and Sp. Def stats.
BTR_STATE_101_01	Guard Drop
BTR_STATE_101_02	The Pokémon’s defensive stats are lowered,\nreducing its Defense and Sp. Def stats.
BTR_STATE_102_01	Strong Sunlight
BTR_STATE_102_02	The Speed of Grass-type Pokémon is boosted.
BTR_STATE_103_01	Fog
BTR_STATE_103_02	All moves are less accurate, apart from moves\nthat are always sure to hit.
BTR_STATE_104_01	Rain
BTR_STATE_104_02	Damage dealt by Fire-type moves is reduced.
BTR_STATE_105_01	Snow
BTR_STATE_105_02	Pokémon are more likely to get frostbite, and\ndrowsy Pokémon are more likely to fail to act.\nThe Speed of Ice-type Pokémon is also boosted.

TOKUSEIINFO_003	Its Speed stat is boosted every turn.
TOKUSEIINFO_004	Hard armor protects the Pokémon from critical hits.
TOKUSEIINFO_005	It cannot be knocked out with one hit. One-hit KO\nmoves cannot knock it out, either.
TOKUSEIINFO_006	Prevents the use of explosive moves, such as\nSelf-Destruct, by dampening its surroundings.
TOKUSEIINFO_007	Its limber body protects the Pokémon from paralysis.
TOKUSEIINFO_008	Boosts the Pokémon’s evasiveness in a sandstorm.
TOKUSEIINFO_009	The Pokémon is charged with static electricity, so\ncontact with it may cause paralysis.
TOKUSEIINFO_010	Restores HP if hit by an Electric-type move instead\nof taking damage.
TOKUSEIINFO_011	Restores HP if hit by a Water-type move instead of\ntaking damage.

TOKUSEIINFO_013	Eliminates the effects of weather.
TOKUSEIINFO_014	The Pokémon’s compound eyes boost its accuracy.
TOKUSEIINFO_015	The Pokémon is suffering from insomnia and cannot\nfall asleep.
TOKUSEIINFO_016	The Pokémon’s type becomes the type of the move\nused on it.
TOKUSEIINFO_017	The immune system of the Pokémon prevents it from\ngetting poisoned.
TOKUSEIINFO_018	Powers up the Pokémon’s Fire-type moves if it’s hit\nby one.
TOKUSEIINFO_019	This Pokémon’s dust blocks the additional effects of\nattacks taken.

TOKUSEIINFO_021	This Pokémon uses suction cups to stay in one spot\nto negate all moves and items that force\nswitching out.
TOKUSEIINFO_022	The Pokémon intimidates opposing Pokémon upon\nentering battle, lowering their Attack stat.
TOKUSEIINFO_023	This Pokémon steps on the opposing Pokémon’s\nshadow to prevent it from escaping.
TOKUSEIINFO_024	This Pokémon inflicts damage with its rough skin\nto the attacker on contact.

TOKUSEIINFO_027	Contact with the Pokémon may inflict poison, sleep,\nor paralysis on its attacker.
TOKUSEIINFO_028	The attacker will receive the same status condition if\nit inflicts a burn, poison, or paralysis to the Pokémon.
TOKUSEIINFO_029	Prevents other Pokémon’s moves or Abilities from\nlowering the Pokémon’s stats.
TOKUSEIINFO_030	All status conditions heal when the Pokémon\nswitches out.

TOKUSEIINFO_034	Boosts the Pokémon’s Speed stat in harsh sunlight.

TOKUSEIINFO_037	Doubles the Pokémon’s Attack stat.
TOKUSEIINFO_038	Contact with the Pokémon may poison the attacker.
TOKUSEIINFO_039	The Pokémon’s intensely focused, and that protects\nthe Pokémon from flinching.
TOKUSEIINFO_040	The Pokémon is covered with hot magma, which\nprevents the Pokémon from becoming frozen.
TOKUSEIINFO_041	The Pokémon is covered with a water veil, which\nprevents the Pokémon from getting a burn.
TOKUSEIINFO_042	Prevents Steel-type Pokémon from escaping using\nits magnetic force.
TOKUSEIINFO_043	Soundproofing gives the Pokémon full\nimmunity to all sound-based moves.
TOKUSEIINFO_044	The Pokémon gradually regains HP in rain.
TOKUSEIINFO_045	The Pokémon summons a sandstorm when it enters\na battle.
TOKUSEIINFO_046	By putting pressure on the opposing Pokémon, it\nraises their PP usage.
TOKUSEIINFO_047	The Pokémon is protected by a layer of thick fat,\nwhich halves the damage taken from Fire- and\nIce-type moves.
TOKUSEIINFO_048	The Pokémon awakens from sleep twice as fast\nas other Pokémon.

TOKUSEIINFO_051	Keen eyes prevent other Pokémon from lowering this\nPokémon’s accuracy.
TOKUSEIINFO_052	The Pokémon’s proud of its powerful pincers. They\nprevent other Pokémon from lowering its Attack stat.

TOKUSEIINFO_054	The Pokémon can’t use a move if it had used a move\non the previous turn.

TOKUSEIINFO_056	Contact with the Pokémon may cause infatuation.

TOKUSEIINFO_059	The Pokémon transforms with the weather to change\nits type to Water, Fire, or Ice.
TOKUSEIINFO_060	Items held by the Pokémon are stuck fast and\ncannot be removed by other Pokémon.

TOKUSEIINFO_063	The Pokémon’s marvelous scales boost the Defense\nstat if it has a status condition.
TOKUSEIINFO_064	The oozed liquid has a strong stench, which damages\nattackers using any draining move.
TOKUSEIINFO_065	Powers up Grass-type moves when the Pokémon’s\nHP is low.
TOKUSEIINFO_066	Powers up Fire-type moves when the Pokémon’s HP\nis low.
TOKUSEIINFO_067	Powers up Water-type moves when the Pokémon’s\nHP is low.
TOKUSEIINFO_068	Powers up Bug-type moves when the Pokémon’s HP\nis low.
TOKUSEIINFO_069	Protects the Pokémon from recoil damage.

ZKN_COMMENT_A_025_000	Possesses cheek sacs in which it stores electricity. This clever\nforest-dweller roasts tough berries with an electric shock before\nconsuming them.
ZKN_COMMENT_A_026_000	It can discharge bursts of electricity exceeding 100,000 volts—\na single strike with that amount of power would incapacitate one\nof the Copperajah of my homeland.
ZKN_COMMENT_A_027_000	[~ 27]

ZKN_COMMENT_A_035_000	It can be found in quiet mountain areas on a full moon’s night.\nIts dancing and its tiny, faintly glowing wings confer upon it a\nlovely fairylike quality.
ZKN_COMMENT_A_036_000	Legend says that on clear, quiet nights, it listens for the voices\nof its kin living on the moon. I, too, often think of my homeland,\nso far away.
ZKN_COMMENT_A_037_000	In its belly burns a fire, which Vulpix spits out in the form of\nfireballs. When young, this Pokémon has but one white tail.\nAs the Pokémon matures, this single tail splits into six.
ZKN_COMMENT_A_038_000	The coat of gleaming golden fur is quite magnificent.\nThis species is said to store sacred power in its nine long tails\nand to live for a millennium.
ZKN_COMMENT_A_039_000	[~ 39]
ZKN_COMMENT_A_040_000	[~ 40]
ZKN_COMMENT_A_041_000	Makes its home in gloomy caves. Atrophied eyes have left this\nPokémon blind, so it scans its surroundings via sound waves that\nit emits from its mouth as it flies.
ZKN_COMMENT_A_042_000	It sinks its sharp fangs into other creatures and slurps up their\nblood. A closer look at the fangs reveals that they are hollow\nand akin to straws.
ZKN_COMMENT_A_043_000	[~ 43]
ZKN_COMMENT_A_044_000	[~ 44]
ZKN_COMMENT_A_045_000	[~ 45]
ZKN_COMMENT_A_046_000	Sometimes seen at the foot of trees in humid forests.\nThe mushrooms on its back—called tochukaso—are not present\non infant specimens and instead emerge as Paras matures.
ZKN_COMMENT_A_047_000	Mushroom-lacking specimens of this Pokémon lie unmoving in\nthe forest, lending credence to the hypothesis that the large\nmushroom is in control of Parasect’s actions.

ZKN_COMMENT_A_055_000	Its body is strong, and it has webbing on its hands and feet.\nGolduck can swim easily through rough seas, clawing its way\nthrough the high waves.

ZKN_COMMENT_A_063_000	Spends 18 hours of the day sleeping. Even while asleep, Abra\ncan control its psychic powers—should danger approach, the\nPokémon will simply teleport away.
ZKN_COMMENT_A_064_000	There are rumors that a child with mystical powers became\na Kadabra; however, this remains unverified. I suspect that\nthe spoon Kadabra holds enhances its brain waves.

ZKN_COMMENT_A_902_001	Clads itself in the souls of comrades that perished before\nfulfilling their goals of journeying upstream. No other species\nthroughout all Hisui’s rivers is Basculegion’s equal.
ZKN_COMMENT_A_905_001	A different guise from its feminine humanoid form. From the\nclouds, it descends upon those who treat any form of life with\ndisrespect and metes out wrathful, ruthless punishment.
